Since today (or the last days) something must have been broken on the JsonReader class currently in maven repository.

I'm reading the following JSON:

{
    "name": "KKnD 1 (complete)",
    "requires": [
        ["kknd1_maps", "1.0.0"],
        ["kknd1_faction_survivors", "1.0.0"],
        ["kknd1_faction_mutants", "1.0.0"]
    ]
}

However the Reader reads it like this:

{
name: "KKnD 1 (complete)",
requires: [
    [
        kknd1_maps,
        "1.0.0"
    ],
    [
        kknd1_faction_survivors,
        "1.0.0"
    ],
    [
        kknd1_faction_mutants,
        "1.0.0"
    ]
]
}

While stripping the quotes for {} objects is valid, its not valid for string values in arrays []. So it breaks reading the json stuff.

java.lang.IllegalStateException: Value cannot be converted to string: stringValue

@bartolkaruza (and maybe other Fragment contributors)
The dispose() is never called when a fragment is detached, do we need to explicitly call something else than the initializeForView in the AndroidFragmentApplication ?

Thanks !

I could be missing something, but the constructors in these classes (maybe more?) could be reduced to one.

[SequenceAction.java](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/blob/master/gdx/src/com/badlogic/gdx/scenes/scene2d/actions/SequenceAction.java)
[ParallelAction.java](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/blob/master/gdx/src/com/badlogic/gdx/scenes/scene2d/actions/ParallelAction.java)

The constructors limit the number of Actions to five (and the initial ArrayList size is four?). Instead the constructor could look something like this:

``` java
public SequenceAction(Action... actions) {
    for(Action action : actions) {
        addAction(action);
    }
}
```

This would allow unlimited Actions in the constructor without changing the syntax.
